name: Dip
description: Dips are like squats for the upper body, blasting your chest, shoulders, and triceps with just your own bodyweight. Their unique pushing motion builds serious strength and stability, making them a gym classic for a reason.

name: Barbell Curl
description: Barbell curls are the ultimate arm sculptor, honing in on your biceps and forearms for that classic ‘gun show’ look. The straight bar keeps both arms working together, making each rep count.

name: Barbell Preacher Curl
description: Barbell preacher curls lock your arms in place, forcing your biceps to do all the work for a serious pump. The preacher bench’s unique angle helps you focus on perfect form and peak contraction.

name: Barbell Row
description: Barbell rows are the back-builder’s best friend, targeting your lats, traps, and rear delts for a thick, strong upper body. The bent-over position also challenges your lower back and grip.

name: Barbell Shrug
description: Barbell shrugs are all about building monstrous traps, giving you that powerful, broad-shouldered look. The simple up-and-down motion is deceptively tough, and your grip gets a workout too.

name: Bench Press
description: Bench press is the king of chest day, firing up your pecs, shoulders, and triceps for serious pushing power. It’s the go-to move for building upper body strength and confidence.

name: Cable Curl
description: Cable curls keep constant tension on your biceps throughout the entire range of motion, making every rep count. The smooth cable action lets you focus on perfect form and a killer squeeze.

name: Chin-Up
description: Chin-ups are the ultimate bodyweight exercise for your biceps and back, lighting up your lats, traps, and arms with every rep. Their underhand grip gives your biceps extra love and makes you feel like a true gym warrior.

name: Crunch
description: Crunches are the classic core move, targeting your abs and obliques for a tight, strong midsection. They’re perfect for beginners and pros alike, and you can do them anywhere.

name: Deadlift
description: Deadlifts are the full-body beast, working your glutes, lower back, and legs for unmatched strength and power. Their unique pulling motion makes you feel unstoppable from the ground up.

name: Dumbbell Bicep Curl
description: Dumbbell bicep curls let you focus on each arm individually, helping you build balanced strength and definition. The free weights add a fun challenge as you work towards bigger, stronger arms.

name: Dumbbell Lateral Raise
description: Dumbbell lateral raises are the secret weapon for wide, sculpted shoulders, directly targeting your side delts and giving you that classic V-shape. The controlled, outward motion makes your shoulders pop.

name: Dumbbell Overhead Press
description: Dumbbell overhead presses are a total shoulder blaster, working all three delt heads, triceps, and traps for balanced upper body strength. Their unique free-weight challenge helps you build power and stability from every angle.

name: Hammer Curl
description: Hammer curls are the arm-thickening move, targeting your brachialis and forearms for a balanced, powerful look. The neutral grip adds a fun twist and builds grip strength for all your lifts.

name: Hanging Knee Raise
description: Hanging knee raises are the ultimate core challenge, lighting up your lower abs, hip flexors and obliques while you hang from a bar. Their unique position tests your grip and endurance.

name: Barbell Hip Thrust
description: Barbell hip thrusts are the glute-building powerhouse, firing up your backside while also working your hamstrings and lower back. Their unique setup maximizes glute activation and helps you build strength for real-world movements.

name: Inverted Row
description: Inverted rows are a fun, scalable bodyweight move that targets your lats, traps, and biceps. The more upright you are, the easier it gets—perfect for all fitness levels.

name: Lat Pull-Down
description: Lat pull-downs are the go-to for a strong, V-shaped back, working your lats, traps, and rear delts with controlled, heavy resistance. The seated setup lets you safely push your limits and build serious pulling power.

name: Machine Bicep Curl
description: Machine bicep curls isolate your arms with a guided motion, letting you focus purely on building bicep strength and definition. The machine’s stability makes it perfect for perfecting form and squeezing out every rep.

name: Machine Chest Fly
description: Machine chest flys isolate your chest muscles, guiding your arms through a wide arc for a deep stretch and strong contraction. The stable seat helps you maintain perfect form and maximize chest activation.

name: Machine Chest Press
description: Machine chest presses efficiently target your chest, shoulders, and triceps with a smooth, guided motion. The machine’s design lets you safely push heavy weights and focus on muscle growth, making it a reliable choice for upper body strength.

name: Machine Shoulder Press
description: Machine shoulder presses target your front delts, triceps, and traps with a stable, controlled movement. The guided path ensures proper form and minimizes injury risk, making it ideal for all experience levels.

name: Military Press
description: Military presses are the classic overhead move, working your front and side delts, triceps, and traps for total shoulder strength. Their strict, upright posture builds power and stability, setting them apart as a true functional movement.

name: Pull-Up
description: Pull-ups are the classic test of upper body strength, targeting your lats and traps while also working your forearms and rear delts. Their bodyweight challenge and versatility make them a staple for building a powerful, sculpted back.

name: Push Press
description: Push presses combine explosive leg power with overhead pressing, working your shoulders, glutes, and quads for total-body strength. This dynamic lift is a favorite among athletes for building power and coordination.

name: Push-Up
description: Push-ups are a timeless bodyweight move, firing up your chest, shoulders, and triceps while secretly engaging your core. Their simplicity and effectiveness make them a must for any fitness routine.

name: Machine Rear Delt Fly
description: Machine rear delt flys isolate your rear delts, helping to balance shoulder development and improve posture. The guided motion ensures you get the most out of each rep while minimizing injury risk.

name: Ring Pull-Up
description: Ring pull-ups add another degree of freedom to the classic pull-up, allowing you to change the angle of your wrist. This can be a good option for you if you find the pull-up or chin-up to be too restrictive.

name: Ring Inverted Row
description: Ring inverted rows, similar to the ring pull-up, add a degree of freedom to the inverted row. This exercise can allow for a deeper range of motion and be easier on your joints compared to the stricter inverted row.

name: Romanian Deadlift
description: Romanian deadlifts focus on your glutes, hamstrings, and lower back, teaching your body to hinge powerfully and safely. Their controlled, smooth motion is ideal for building strength and proper lifting mechanics.

name: Barbell Squat
description: Barbell squats are the ultimate leg builder, working your quads, glutes, and core for unmatched lower body strength. Their strict form and full-body engagement make them a gym classic.

name: Zercher Squat
description: Zercher squats are a unique squat variation that cradles the bar in your elbows, challenging your quads, glutes, and upper back in one move. Their unconventional setup builds both strength and toughness.

name: Pike Push-Up
description: Pike push-ups target your shoulders and triceps from a unique upside-down angle, helping you build overhead strength and stability. This bodyweight move is a stepping stone to handstand push-ups.

name: Weighted Dip
description: Weighted dips take your chest, triceps, and shoulders to the next level, letting you add extra resistance for serious upper body gains. Their versatility and effectiveness make them a favorite for advanced lifters.

name: Ring Push-Up
description: Ring push-ups are a fun challenge for your chest, shoulders, and triceps, with the instability of the rings forcing your core and stabilizers to work overtime. Every rep is a mini-adventure in strength and control.

name: Ring Tricep Extension
description: Ring tricep extensions isolate your triceps while the rings add a fun, unstable element to each rep. This exercise is perfect for building strong, sculpted arms with rings.

name: Weighted Pull-Up
description: Weighted pull-ups add extra resistance to the classic pull-up, making your lats, traps, and biceps work even harder. They’re the ultimate badge of upper body strength and endurance.

name: Ring Arc Row
description: Ring arc rows is unique compared to the inverted row or ring inverted row, in that you pull the rings to your hips instead of your chest, frying every inch of your lats. This move is the stepping stone to front lever holds.

name: Ring Face Pull
description: Ring face pulls are a fun way to target your rear delts and traps, helping you build balanced shoulders and improve posture. The rings allow your joints move freely.

name: Pistol Squat
description: Pistol squats are the single-leg daredevil of lower body moves, blasting your quads and glutes while testing your balance and mobility. Their unique one-legged stance is perfect for building strength, coordination, and confidence.

name: Hollow Body Hold
description: The hollow body hold is a core classic, lighting up your abs as you maintain a tight, 'hollow' core. This static move is a staple in gymnastics and fitness for building rock-solid core strength and stability.

name: Landmine 180
description: Landmine 180s are a dynamic core crusher, targeting your obliques and abs as you rotate the barbell from side to side. This rotational move is unique for building functional core power and athleticism.

name: Neck Flexion
description: Neck flexion is a simple but effective move for strengthening your neck flexors, helping to support good posture and reduce injury risk.

name: Neck Extension
description: Neck extension targets your neck extensors, building strength and stability for a resilient neck. This move is essential for athletes and anyone looking to keep their neck mobile and strong.

name: Neck Side Flexion
description: Neck side flexion works your neck flexors and extensors together, building balanced neck strength from all angles. It’s a smart move for comprehensive neck health and injury prevention.

name: Ring Dip
description: Ring dips are a next-level upper body challenge, targeting your chest, shoulders, and triceps while the rings add a fun wobble. This move is perfect for those who want to build serious pushing strength and control.

name: Ring Curl
description: Ring curls are a creative twist on the classic bicep move. They’re perfect for building arm strength with a gymnastics flavor.

name: L-Sit
description: The L-sit is a core and hip flexor test, challenging you to hold your legs straight out in front while supporting yourself with your hands. This static hold is a favorite for building serious core compression and control.

name: Cable Tricep Extension
description: Cable tricep extensions keep constant tension on your triceps for maximum muscle activation. The smooth cable action lets you focus on perfect form and a killer squeeze.

name: Seated Cable Row
description: Seated cable rows are a go-to for a strong, sculpted back, targeting your lats, traps, and rear delts with controlled resistance. This move is perfect for building pulling power and posture.

name: Leg Extension
description: Leg extensions isolate your quads for a focused, muscle-building burn. The machine’s guided motion makes it easy to perfect your form and push your limits.

name: Nordic Hamstring Curl
description: Nordic hamstring curls are a bodyweight beast, blasting your hamstrings, glutes, and lower back for serious posterior chain strength. This move is a favorite for athletes and anyone looking to build resilient legs.

name: Seated Leg Curl
description: Seated leg curls target your hamstrings with a smooth, controlled motion, making it easy to focus on perfect form. This move is a staple for strong, balanced legs.

name: L-Sit Pull-Up
description: L-sit pull-ups combine the core stability of the L-sit with the pulling power of a pull-up, lighting up your lats, traps, abs, and hip flexors. This advanced move is perfect for those who love a full-body challenge.

name: Handstand Push-Up
description: Handstand push-ups are the ultimate bodyweight shoulder blaster, targeting your front, side, and rear delts, triceps, and traps. This upside-down move is a true test of strength, balance, and technique.

name: Handstand Hold
description: Handstand holds are the ultimate test of shoulder strength and stability, lighting up your front, side, and rear delts while also challenging your triceps and traps. This static move is a favorite among gymnasts and fitness enthusiasts for building total upper body control.

name: Front Leg Elevated Split Squat
description: Front leg elevated split squats add a twist to the classic lunge, targeting your quads and glutes with a unique balance challenge. This move is perfect for building single-leg strength and mobility.

name: Bulgarian Split Squat
description: Bulgarian split squats are the unliateral lower body powerhouse, focusing on your quads and glutes while your back leg rests on a bench. This move is a favorite for building strength, balance, and coordination while addressing any imbalances.

name: Tibialis Curls
description: Tibialis curls isolate your tibialis anterior, strengthening your shins for better ankle health and injury prevention. This unique move is a secret weapon for athletes and runners.

name: Weighted Ring Dip
description: Weighted ring dips take upper body pushing to new heights, targeting your chest, shoulders, and triceps while the instability of the rings adds a fun challenge. Strap on some weight and watch your strength soar.

name: Vertical Knee Raise
description: Vertical knee raises are a core classic, blasting your abs, obliques, and hip flexors as you lift your knees toward your chest. This move is perfect for building a strong, stable midsection and can help you get your first L-Sit.

name: Vertical Leg Raise
description: Vertical leg raises are a step up from the vertical knee raise in intensity. The straight legs demand more from your abs, obliques, and hip flexors. This move is a favorite for building serious abdominal strength.

name: Hollow Body Pull-Up
description: Hollow body pull-ups combine the pulling power of a pull-up with the core strength of the hollow body position, lighting up your lats, traps, abs, and hip flexors. This advanced move is perfect for those who love a full-body challenge.

name: Cable Fly
description: Cable flies are a chest-building favorite, offering constant tension as you bring your arms together in a smooth arc. This move is perfect for sculpting your pecs and improving muscle symmetry.

name: Cable High-Low Fly
description: Cable high-low flies target your chest from a unique angle, starting high and finishing low for a full-range stretch and contraction. This variation keeps your lower chest muscles guessing and growing.

name: Cable Low-High Fly
description: Cable low-high flies flip the script, starting low and finishing high for a different chest challenge. This move is perfect for building upper chest strength and definition.

name: Dumbbell Bench Press
description: Dumbbell bench presses are a versatile chest builder, targeting your pecs, shoulders, and triceps with a greater range of motion. The free weights add a fun stability challenge and promote balanced muscle development.

name: Machine Shrug
description: Machine shrugs are a trap-building staple, focusing on your upper back while your forearms get a workout too. The guided motion ensures perfect form and maximum muscle engagement.

name: Hack Squat
description: Hack squats are a leg day favorite, putting your quads in the spotlight while also working your glutes, hamstrings, and calves. The machine’s angled track supports your back and lets you push heavy for serious lower body gains.

name: Incline Bench Press
description: Incline bench presses target your upper chest, front delts, and triceps, giving your pecs a powerful lift and shape. The angled bench adds a fresh twist to classic pressing for a well-rounded chest.

name: Leg Press
description: Leg presses are a powerhouse move for your quads and glutes, with backup from your hamstrings and calves. The machine lets you load up safely, making it perfect for building strong, muscular legs and impressing other gym-goers.

name: Machine Calf Extension
description: Machine calf extensions isolate your calves for a focused, muscle-building burn. The seated or standing machine keeps the motion smooth and lets you really squeeze at the top for maximum growth.

name: Machine Incline Press
description: Machine incline presses deliver upper chest gains with the support of a guided path, taking pressure off your shoulders and joints. This move is great for safely pushing heavy and building a strong, defined chest.

name: Machine Leg Press
description: Machine leg presses are a great choice for beginners. They power up your quads and glutes while your hamstrings and calves assist. The machine’s stability helps you lock in your connection to your lower body.

name: Seated Dumbbell Overhead Press
description: Seated dumbbell overhead presses fire up all three heads of your delts, plus your triceps and traps, for balanced shoulder strength. The seated position helps you lift safely and evenly.

name: Supine Press
description: Supine presses are a chest-building classic, working your pecs, front delts, and triceps as you press from a flat position. This move is a go-to for building a strong, solid upper body foundation.

name: Handstand Hold (Bent Arm)
description: The bent arm handstand hold focuses on the bottom position of a handstand push-up, where your elbows are bent and your body hovers just above the ground. This static hold builds serious strength in your shoulders, triceps, and upper back while training control and stability in one of the most demanding support positions.
